Kubernetes Cluster
       ↓
Node Exporter (collects node metrics)
       ↓
Prometheus (stores metrics)
       ↓
Grafana (visual dashboards)
       ↓
Alertmanager (alerts)
___________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Install Helm
helm version

If Helm is not installed:

curl https://raw.githubusercontent.com/helm/helm/main/scripts/get-helm-3 | bash
2. Create Monitoring Namespace
kubectl create namespace monitoring

Verify:

kubectl get ns
3. Add Prometheus Helm Repository
helm repo add prometheus-community https://prometheus-community.github.io/helm-charts

Update repo:

helm repo update
4. Install kube-prometheus-stack

This installs:

Prometheus

Grafana

Alertmanager

Node Exporter

kube-state-metrics

Run:

helm install monitoring prometheus-community/kube-prometheus-stack -n monitoring
5. Verify Installation

Check pods:

kubectl get pods -n monitoring

Expected pods:

monitoring-grafana
prometheus-monitoring-kube-prometheus-prometheus
monitoring-kube-state-metrics
monitoring-prometheus-node-exporter
alertmanager-monitoring-kube-prometheus-alertmanager

All should show:

Running
6. Check Services
kubectl get svc -n monitoring

Example output:

monitoring-grafana
monitoring-kube-prometheus-prometheus
monitoring-kube-state-metrics
7. Expose Grafana (LoadBalancer)

Edit Grafana service:

kubectl edit svc monitoring-grafana -n monitoring

Change:

type: ClusterIP

to

type: LoadBalancer

Save and exit.

8. Get Grafana URL

Run:

kubectl get svc -n monitoring

Example:

monitoring-grafana   LoadBalancer   EXTERNAL-IP

Open in browser:

http://<LOADBALANCER-URL>
9. Login to Grafana

Default credentials:

Username: admin
Password: prom-operator

If password doesn't work:

kubectl get secret monitoring-grafana -n monitoring \
-o jsonpath="{.data.admin-password}" | base64 --decode
10. Verify Prometheus

Port-forward Prometheus:

kubectl port-forward svc/monitoring-kube-prometheus-prometheus -n monitoring 9090

Open:

http://localhost:9090

Check:

Status → Targets

All targets should be UP.

11. Test Metrics

In Prometheus query:

up

You should see multiple targets with value 1.

12. Import Grafana Dashboards

Go to:

Grafana → Dashboards → New → Import

Import these dashboards.

Node Monitoring Dashboard
1860

Shows:

CPU

Memory

Disk

Network

Kubernetes Cluster Dashboard
15757

Shows:

Node health

Pod metrics

Cluster usage

13. Verify Metrics in Grafana

Go to:

Explore → Prometheus

Run query:

up

Graph should appear.

14. Useful Prometheus Queries
CPU Usage
100 - (avg by(instance) (irate(node_cpu_seconds_total{mode="idle"}[5m])) * 100)
Memory Usage
node_memory_MemAvailable_bytes
Pod Count
count(kube_pod_info)
15. Monitoring Stack Components
Component	Purpose
Prometheus	Metrics collection
Grafana	Visualization
Node Exporter	Node metrics
kube-state-metrics	Kubernetes metrics
Alertmanager	Alerting system
16. Final Verification

Check everything:

kubectl get pods -n monitoring
kubectl get svc -n monitoring

Grafana dashboard should display metrics.
